04977nam a22008775i 9783110729900DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20212022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107299007 a10.1515/97831107299002doi  a(DE-B1597)572877  a(OCoLC)1286806729  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aNX456.5.N49bL38 2022 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a709.04072231 aLau, Jordis , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAppropriations of Literary Modernism in Media Art :bCultural Memory and the Dynamics of Estrangement /cJordis Lau. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (VIII, 239 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMedia and Cultural Memory / Medien und kulturelle Erinnerung ,x1613-8961 ;v33  aDiss.cUniversität Hamburg.00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- t1 Introduction -- t2 Appropriation, Estrangement, Memories: Theoretical Configurations -- t3 Actualizing Modernism: Case Studies -- t4 Conclusion -- tWorks Cited -- tList of Figures -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy analyzing appropriations of literary modernism in video, experimental film, and installation art, this study investigates works of media art as agents of cultural memory. While research recognizes film and literature as media of memory, it often overlooks media art. Adaptation studies, art history, and hermeneutics help understand ‘appropriation’ in art in terms of a dialog between an artwork, a text, and their contexts. The Russian Formalist notion of estrangement, together with new concepts from literary, film, and media studies, offers a new perspective on ‘appropriation’ that illuminates the sensuous dimension of cultural memory . Media artworks make memory palpable: they address the collective body memory of their viewers, prompting them to reflect on the past and embody new ways of remembering. Five contextual close-readings analyze artworks by Janis Crystal Lipzin, William Kentridge, Mark Aerial Waller, Paweł Wojtasik, and Tom Kalin. They appropriate modernist texts by Gertrude Stein, Italo Svevo, Louis-Ferdinand Céline, Guillaume Apollinaire, Virginia Woolf, and Robert Musil. This book will be of value to readers interested in cultural memory, sensory studies, literary modernism, adaptation studies, and art history.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aModernism (Art). 0aModernism (Literature). 0aNew media art. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aSensuous memory.  aestrangement.  aliterary modernism.  amedia art.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1z978311076682008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishz978311075412408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021z9783110753899oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831107299860 cprintz978311072088440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311072990040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110729900423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110729900/original  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075412-4  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-076682-0  DG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGru